==English==
===Etymology===
Probably of [[Semitic]] origin (see Hebrew ''saq'', Akkadian ''saqqu''), entering Greek (''sakkos'', a bag of coarse cloth) via Phonecian, then Latin (''saccus'', a large bag) &rarr; Germanic ''*sakkiz'' &rarr; Old English (''sæc'', from *sakkiz, and ''sacc'', directly from Latin, from which comes the modern English word '''sack''').

Also borrowed from Greek or Latin are cognates in Welsh, Russian, Polish and Albanian. 

===Noun===
'''sack'''
# [[bag]], device for carrying things in
# Dismissal from employment ("She got the sack").
# An old English measure of weight, usually of wool, containing 13 stone or 182 pounds.
#:'''Quotations'''
#:*'''1882''': Generally, however, the stone or petra, almost always of 14 lbs., is used, the tod of 28 lbs., and the sack of thirteen stone. &mdash; James Edwin Thorold Rogers, ''A History of Agriculture and Prices in England'', Volume 4, p. 209.
#(slang) bed ''(I'm tired, I'm going to hit the sack)''
#a variety of wine from Spain or the Canary Islands
